post_text: CHS students in Rachel Goeden's Intermediate Sculpture class make pieces with materials they have at home. For her mixed media piece called, DREAMS LOST senior Emily Stark says she was, "inspired by everything going on in the world currently. I wanted to create a sculpture that depicts a virus. It has made such an impact on my and everyone's life I thought it was fitting. Using materials from my house, I painted and added moss on a styrofoam ball and then cut colored pencils at different lengths and drilled them into the balls."
text: CHS students in Rachel Goeden's Intermediate Sculpture class make pieces with materials they have at home. For her mixed media piece called, DREAMS LOST senior Emily Stark says she was, "inspired by everything going on in the world currently. I wanted to create a sculpture that depicts a virus. It has made such an impact on my and everyone's life I thought it was fitting. Using materials from my house, I painted and added moss on a styrofoam ball and then cut colored pencils at different lengths and drilled them into the balls."

post_text: At this time there have been no confirmed cases or links to cases of the COVID-19 virus in Central 301. As a precautionary measure, the District has canceled all after school activities, athletics, and events for today, Thursday, March 12th and tomorrow, Friday, March 13th as we await guidance from local health and government agencies. After-school care at the elementary schools will continue as usual. There are no plans to cancel school at this time.

post_text: Congratulations to this outstanding CMS musician! Rowyn won 1st place at the State Composition Contest Awards and Recital in Peoria for his instrumental solo, “Dreamception.” He also earned 3rd place for his small ensemble piece, “A Busy Cafe.” Rowyn received his two awards for his compositions at an awards ceremony in front of music educators from around the state and many talented student musicians. He also received a $100 scholarship to a compositional camp called ISYM at the University of Illinois this summer.

He also received a $100 scholarship to a compositional camp called ISYM at the University of Illinois this summer.

post_text: Prairie Knolls Middle School students are making an impact on the community! In the spirit of giving and sharing with others, the S.T.A.R. Club (Students That Accept Responsibility) is sponsoring a new event this year to provide needed items for the homeless at this time of year. The so-called GRAND GIVING OF GIFTS designates a specific item each day in December. Collected gifts will be loaded into a backpack and ultimately donated to a local homeless shelter. For more information and a donation calendar, visit Principal Haug's weekly message https://pkms.central301.net/principals-message/
